'''Toshi Shrine''' (としじんじゃ, {{Lang-en|Toshi Jinja}}) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kakegawa City|Q823988|WD=Q823988|1=Kakegawa, Shizuoka}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320|WD=Q131320|1=Shizuoka Prefecture}}. Under the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=ancient shrine ranking system|1=UNKNOWN}}, its {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} is {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha (minor shrine)|Q134917287|WD=Q134917287|1=Shikinai Shosha}}. Under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, its rank is {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

=== Overview ===
It is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Shimomata-Minami, {{ill|lt=Kakegawa City|Q823988|WD=Q823988|1=Kakegawa, Shizuoka}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320|WD=Q131320|1=Shizuoka Prefecture}}<ref name="nta20151113"/><ref>“Toshi Shrine,” “[http://www.shizuoka-jinjacho.or.jp/shokai/jinja.php?id=4409002 Toshi Shrine - Shizuoka Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines]” {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines|Q134956727|WD=Q134956727|1=Shizuoka Prefectural Shrine Association}}.</ref>. It enshrines two deities, {{ill|lt=Ōtoshi-no-Kami|Q3028663|WD=Q3028663|1=Toshigami}} and {{ill|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Kami|Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|1=Ukanomitama}}<ref name="shikinaishaToshiJinja"/><ref name="mre1925_289"/>, and counts as its {{ill|lt=ujiko|Q125562175|WD=Q125562175|1=Ujiko}} the residents of the Shimomata-chō Ward, Chūō 2-chōme Ward, Jūkyūshu Ward, Odaka-chō Ward, Chūō 3-chōme Ward, and Chūō-Takamachi Ward, which are districts of Kakegawa City<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>. It is identified with the “Toshi &#xfa19;&#xfa4c;” listed as a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha (minor shrine)|Q134917287|WD=Q134917287|1=Shikinai Shosha}} in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}<ref name="masamune1929_128">{{ill|lt=Atsuo Masamune|Q3297160|WD=Q3297160|1=Masamune Atsuo}} (ed.), “Engishiki,” vol. 2, Nihon Koten Zenshū Kankōkai, 1929, p. 128.</ref><ref name="mre1925_289"/><ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>. During the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it held joint festivals together with {{ill|lt=Ryūbi Shrine|Q11679232|WD=Q11679232|1=Tatsuo Shrine}} and {{ill|lt=Shinmei Shrine (Nito, Kakegawa)|Q118146837|WD=Q118146837|lt=Shinmei Shrine|1=Shinmei-gū}}<ref name="kakegawa201801_77">{{ill|lt=Kakegawa City Hall|Q109594222|WD=Q109594222|lt=Kakegawa City|1=Kakegawa City Office}} “Kakegawa City Plan for the Maintenance and Improvement of Historic Landscape,” January 2018, p. 77.</ref>, which is known as the origin of today’s {{ill|lt=Kakegawa Festival|Q11498235|WD=Q11498235|1=Kakegawa Matsuri}}<ref name="kakegawa201801_77"/>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Ōtoshi-no-Kami|Q3028663|WD=Q3028663|1=Toshigami}}<ref name="shikinaishaToshiJinja"/><ref name="mre1925_289"/>
* {{ill|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Kami|Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|1=Ukanomitama}}<ref name="shikinaishaToshiJinja"/><ref name="mre1925_289"/>

=== History ===
The date of its founding is unknown<ref name="shikinaishaToshiJinja"/><ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>. However, since “Toshi &#xfa19;&#xfa4c;” is listed as a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha (minor shrine)|Q134917287|WD=Q134917287|lt=minor shrine|1=Shikinai Shosha}} of {{ill|lt=Sano District, Tōtōmi Province|Q11385111|WD=Q11385111|1=Saya district}} in volume 9 of the “{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}},” which was compiled in 927 ({{ill|lt=Enchō (era)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|1=Enchō}} 5)<ref name="masamune1929_128"/><ref group="†">{{ill|lt=Sano District, Shizuoka|Q11385111|WD=Q11385111|1=Saya district}} was merged with {{ill|lt=Jōtō District|Q11426221|WD=Q11426221|1=Kitō district}} to form {{ill|lt=Ogasa District|Q7079825|WD=Q7079825|1=Ogasa District, Shizuoka}} in 1896.</ref>, it is presumed that the shrine was founded prior to 927. The “Engishiki” is a legal code of the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, compiled by {{ill|lt=Fujiwara no Tokihira|Q2994735|WD=Q2994735|1=Fujiwara no Tokihira}} and {{ill|lt=Fujiwara no Tadahira|Q1397601|WD=Q1397601|1=Fujiwara no Tadahira}} under the order of {{ill|lt=Emperor Daigo|Q329753|WD=Q329753|1=Emperor Daigo}}. The lists of shrines recorded in volumes 9 and 10 are known as the Engishiki Jinmyōchō, and the shrines listed therein were called {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}.

In the Edo period, it was generously protected by the {{ill|lt=Kakegawa Domain|Q3034456|WD=Q3034456|1=Kakegawa Domain}}<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/> and revered by the people as a guardian shrine of the western part of {{ill|lt=Kakegawa-juku|Q3070229|WD=Q3070229|1=Kakegawa-juku}} in Sano District<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/><ref group="†">{{ill|lt=Kakegawa-juku|Q3070229|WD=Q3070229|1=Kakegawa-juku}} and parts of Shimomata-chō, Jūkyūshu-chō, Nitō Village, Ōike Village, and Kuzukawa Village were merged in 1889 to establish {{ill|lt=Kakegawa Town|Q823988|WD=Q823988|lt=Kakegawa|1=Kakegawa, Shizuoka}}.</ref>. In 1743 (lunar calendar, {{ill|lt=Kanpō|Q1145798|WD=Q1145798|1=Kanpō}} 3, 2nd month, 21st day), {{ill|lt=Ogasawara Nagayasu|Q8515344|WD=Q8515344|1=Ogasawara Nagayuki}}, heir to the domain lord, paid a visit<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>, and a record remains stating that he donated a pair of heishi (sake bottles) and one bu of gold on that occasion<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>. A ridge tag also remains indicating that the main shrine was rebuilt in 1644 (lunar calendar, {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|WD=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 4, 9th month)<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>.

After the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}<ref name="shikinaishaToshiJinja"/><ref name="mre1925_289"/><ref name="suzuki1908_150"/>. Although records do not clearly indicate when the {{ill|lt=haiden|Q3125745|WD=Q3125745|1=Haiden (Shinto)}} was roofed with tiles<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>, the buildings were rebuilt in 1915 ({{ill|lt=Taishō|Q329174|WD=Q329174|1=Taishō era}} 4)<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>. In September 1926 (Taishō 15), the {{ill|lt=kagura hall|Q94498|WD=Q94498|1=Kagura-den}} was rebuilt<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>.

=== Examination regarding its status as a Shikinaisha ===
=== Engishiki ===
[[File:Engishiki cropped Engishiki Vol 2 Flame 69.jpg|thumb|200px|The section in volume 9 of the “{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}” included in the Nihon Koten Zenshū that mentions “Toshi &#xfa19;&#xfa4c;”<ref name="masamune1929_128"/>]]
The shrine’s origin record clearly states that it is a “Shikinaisha”<ref name="shikinaishaToshiJinja"/>, and Toshi Shrine is regarded as the Shikinaisha listed in the Engishiki Jinmyōchō<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>. However, since the Engishiki dates back to the Heian period, many Shikinaisha lost identifiable descendants over time. As a result, scholars of National Learning conducted long-term research to identify their successors, and the successor of the “Toshi &#xfa19;&#xfa4c;” has been debated repeatedly. Regarding its reading, volume 9 of the Engishiki in the Nihon Koten Zenshū gives furigana reading “Toshino” for “Toshi”<ref name="masamune1929_128"/>.

=== Jinmyōchō kōshō ===
[[File:Ban Nobutomo Zenshu cropped Ban Nobutomo Zenshu Vol 1 Frame 121.jpg|thumb|200px|A section in “&#xfa19;meichō Kōshō” included in the Ban Nobutomo Zenshū that discusses “Toshi &#xfa19;&#xfa4c;”<ref name="ichishima1907_226">{{ill|lt=Kenkichi Ichishima|Q11480125|WD=Q11480125|1=Kenkichi Ichishima}} (ed.), “Ban Nobutomo Zenshū,” vol. 1, {{ill|lt=Kokusho Kankōkai (1905–1922)|Q28686029|WD=Q28686029|1=Kokusho Kankōkai (1905–1922)}}, 1907, p. 226.</ref>]]
The Edo-period scholar {{ill|lt=Ban Nobutomo|Q4346747|WD=Q4346747|1=Ban Nobutomo}} researched ancient shrines and authored “{{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō Kōshō (Dai)|Q11588823|WD=Q11588823|lt=Jinmyōchō Kōshō|1=Jinmyōchō Kōshō Dodai}}.” In it, he also discusses the “Toshi &#xfa19;&#xfa4c;” of the Engishiki Jinmyōchō, introducing the theory that “west of Kakegawa-juku there is a place called Jūkyūshu, where there is Toshi Daimyōjin; this must be it”<ref name="ichishima1907_226"/>. Regarding its reading, he gives furigana “Tokami” for “Toshi”<ref name="ichishima1907_226"/>.

=== Jinja Kakuroku ===
[[File:Jinja Kakuroku cropped Jinja Kakuroku Part Jo Frame 439.jpg|thumb|200px|A section in the upper volume of “{{ill|lt=Jinja Kakuroku|Q11590708|WD=Q11590708|lt=&#xfa19;&#xfa4c; Kakuroku|1=Jinja Kakuroku}}” discussing “Toshi &#xfa19;&#xfa4c;”<ref name="suzuka1902_857">{{ill|lt=Suzuka Tsugutane|Q6536446|WD=Q6536446|lt=Nakatomi no Asomi Tsugutane|1=Suzuka Tsuratane}} (sel.), “Tōtōmi Province,” authored by Suzuka Yoshikujira; edited by {{ill|lt=Yorikuni Inoue|Q6535302|WD=Q6535302|1=Inoue Yorikuni}} and {{ill|lt=Ariyoshi Saeki|Q11382847|WD=Q11382847|1=Saeki Ariyoshi}}, “&#xfa19;&#xfa4c; Kakuroku,” upper volume, {{ill|lt=Kōten Kōkyūjo|Q11580997|WD=Q11580997|1=Koten Kokyusho}}, 1902, p. 857.</ref>]]
On the other hand, the Edo-period Shinto priest {{ill|lt=Suzuka Tsugutane|Q6536446|WD=Q6536446|1=Suzuka Tsuratane}} also researched ancient shrines and authored the “{{ill|lt=Jinja Kakuroku|Q11590708|WD=Q11590708|1=Jinja Kakuroku}}.” Therein, he states regarding the “Toshi &#xfa19;&#xfa4c;” of the Engishiki Jinmyōchō that the details of the enshrined deity and location were already unknown<ref name="suzuka1902_857"/>. He then introduces the same theory that “west of Kakegawa-juku there is a place called Jūkyūshu, where there is Toshi Daimyōjin; this must be it”<ref name="suzuka1902_857"/>. Regarding its reading, he states that “Toshi should be read as ‘To’”<ref name="suzuka1902_857"/>.

=== Tokusen Shimmeichō ===
In the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era|WD=Q3125096}}, research into ancient shrines also progressed within the {{ill|lt=Ministry of Religion|Q4294653|WD=Q4294653|1=Ministry of Religion (Japan)}}, one of the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=central government ministries|1=UNKNOWN}}, and the results were published as the “{{ill|lt=Tokusen Shimmeichō|Q11571092|WD=Q11571092|1=Tokusen Jinmyōchō}}.” In it, the location of the “Toshi &#xfa19;&#xfa4c;” of the Engishiki Jinmyōchō is clearly identified as “Kamegaya aza, Shimomata Village ({{ill|lt=Ogasa District|Q7079825|WD=Q7079825|1=Ogasa District, Shizuoka}}{{ill|lt=Kakegawa Town|Q823988|WD=Q823988|lt=Kakegawa|1=Kakegawa, Shizuoka}}{{ill|lt=ōaza|Q424857|WD=Q424857|1=ōaza}} Shimomata)”<ref name="mre1925_289"/>, making a definitive identification. Regarding its reading, furigana “Toshikami-no” is given for “Toshi”<ref name="mre1925_289"/>.

=== Shrine precincts ===
Within the precincts stand a haiden with a heiden attached, covering the {{ill|lt=main hall|Q2044994|WD=Q2044994|1=Honden}} of {{ill|lt=kokerabuki|Q199388|WD=Q199388|1=Wood shingle}} {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|WD=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}} style<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>, as well as a kagura hall<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>. Behind the precincts is Toshigami Pond<ref name="kakegawa201801_79"/>. Adjacent to the precincts is Toshigami Park<ref>“Toshigami Park,” “[https://www.city.kakegawa.shizuoka.jp/gyosei/docs/11065.html Toshigami Park - Kakegawa City]” {{ill|lt=Kakegawa City Hall|Q109594222|WD=Q109594222|1=Kakegawa City Office}}, November 21, 2014.</ref>.

=== Festivals and annual events ===
Known festivals include the Gion Festival and the Autumn Festival. Prior to the Meiji period, the Gion Festival was held on June 15<ref name="kakegawa201801_80"/>, and the Autumn Festival on September 14<ref name="kakegawa201801_80"/>. From 1920 (Taishō 9), the Gion and Autumn festivals have been held jointly in October<ref name="kakegawa201801_80"/>.

Toshi Shrine also conducts the Kakegawa Festival as a joint festival of seven shrines together with Ryūbi Shrine, Shinmei Shrine, Ikebe Shrine, Hakusan Shrine, Tsushima Shrine, and Kifune Shrine<ref name="kakegawa201801_77"/>. Originally, the Kakegawa Festival originated from festivals jointly conducted by Toshi Shrine with Ryūbi Shrine and Shinmei Shrine<ref name="kakegawa201801_77"/>, and is said to have been held since the mid-Edo period<ref name="kakegawa201801_77"/>. In the Edo period, it was rare nationwide for multiple shrines to jointly conduct a festival<ref name="kakegawa201801_84">{{ill|lt=Kakegawa City Hall|Q109594222|WD=Q109594222|lt=Kakegawa City|1=Kakegawa City Office}} “Kakegawa City Plan for the Maintenance and Improvement of Historic Landscape,” January 2018, p. 84.</ref>. At the time, Kakegawa-juku was located within the sōguruwa (overall enclosure) of Kakegawa Castle<ref name="kakegawa201801_84"/>. As a result, unlike other castle towns, the samurai quarter and the post town were integrated<ref name="kakegawa201801_84"/>, and the parish areas of the three shrines—Ryūbi Shrine, Shinmei Shrine, and Toshi Shrine—were intermingled, which formed the background for this arrangement<ref name="kakegawa201801_84"/>.

